      "content": "The MACRS (Modified Accelerated Cost Recovery System) depreciation formula for a 7-year property class is:\n\nMACRS Depreciation = (Cost of Equipment - Residual Value) / Useful Life\n\nFor the first year, the MACRS depreciation rate is 20%. This is because the equipment is considered to be 20% worn out or used up in the first year, which is why it's called the \"20% depletion\" year.\n\nTo calculate the first year's depreciation, you can use the following formula:\n\nYear 1 Depreciation = Cost of Equipment x 20% = 0.20 x Cost of Equipment\n\nFor example, if the cost of the equipment is $100,000, the first year's depreciation would be $20,000.\n\nKeep in mind that the residual value is not specified, so you'll need to estimate it or use a different method to determine the first year's depreciation. It's also worth noting that the IRS has specific guidelines for estimating the residual value, which can be found in the Internal Revenue Code (IRC) section 167.",
